<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-141-566  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 141 566.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  April 1989 v14 n4 p209(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The CASE philosophy. (Computer-aided software engineering)(contains a related article on the Center for Advanced InformationManagement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gibson, Michael Lucas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-aided software engineering (CASE) provides a modelingtool that describes a business, corporate planning, or businessenvironment and documents computer-systems development fromplanning through implementation.andP;  Upper level CASE uses softwareto describe the company and its plans.andP;  It helps to understand acompany's direction and how to contribute to its success.andP;  It alsoperforms 'what if' analyses and assesses best- and worst-casescenarios.andP;  Middle level CASE analyzes problems and designssolutions to them.andP;  It provides easier methods for changingsystems designs.andP;  It also facilitates joint applications-designsessions and allows analysts to create screens to simulate the I-Oscreens and reports to be used as the end-user interface.andP;  Lowerlevel CASE uses developmental software to create a set of systemsdevelopment specifications that are used to generate programs andtheir user documentation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-aided software engineeringBusiness PlanningSoftware packages.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   A fully integrated CASE environment. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>